Analysis for Winnie

1 Setup

Turnout = read.csv ("http://www.sfu.ca/~sweldon/Final.csv")
DT::datatable(Turnout, options = list(scrollX = TRUE)) #don't include this line - this is just to visualize the table

1.2 Requirements

  • Univariate Analyses (especially for the Dependent Variable).
  • Bivariate Analyses
  • Multiple Regression
  • Robustness Checks for outliers and influence points
  • Correctly run all statistical analyses, including at least 3 different types of bivariate analyses (remember there are 4 basic types:
    • T-Test
    • Chi-Square
    • ANOVA
    • Pearson’s R correlation coefficient

1.3 The hypothesies to test:

  1. Compulsory voting would have a direct effect on increasing voter turnout. Every eligible voter would be obliged to vote during elections, or otherwise face punitive measures, therefore ensuring a large voter turnout.
  2. Countries using the majoritarian (or plurality) system generally have a lower voter turnout. This system is often viewed as unfair as it is possible for a party to win a majority of seats in the HOC even if it wins less than half of the total votes. This system tends to over-represent one point of view and significantly under-represent or eliminate other viewpoints, making citizens feel like their votes are wasted. (Countries using the proportional representation systems tend to have higher voter turnout because each vote is treated fairly and equally. – should I add this? Or not necessary?)
  3. Higher electoral competitiveness increases voter turnout because the uncertainty about the outcome and the feeling that your side has a decent chance to win encourages more citizens to vote
  4. A country with a population who has higher education will result in a higher voter turnout. People who have received more education are regarded as having more knowledge about politics than those who did not receive much education.

But before I do this I’m going to look at the turnout variable:

2 The effect of compulsory voting

Compulsory voting would have a direct effect on increasing voter turnout.

The column name is compulsory

2.1 Univariate analysis

Using a bar chart

ggplot(Turnout, aes(compulsory)) +
  geom_bar()

2.2 Bivariate analysis

2.2.1 Plot

Using boxplot

ggplot(Turnout, aes(compulsory, turnout)) +
  geom_boxplot()

2.2.2 Statistical test - ANOVA

  • Null: there is no relationship between turnout and compulsory
  • Alternate: there is a relationship between turnout and compulsory
anova(lm(turnout ~ compulsory, Turnout))
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: turnout
##            Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(>F)    
## compulsory  2  3646.9  1823.5  9.2234 0.0002683 ***
## Residuals  73 14432.2   197.7                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Pvalue is 0.0002683, which is below the 0.05 threshold. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis and lend support for the alternative hypothesis: there is a relationship between compulsory and turnout

2.2.3 Statistical test - T-test

The difference here is that we are directly comparing two groups, whereas before we were comparing all groups

  • Null: countries with Not Enforced have same turnout as countries without compulsory voting
  • Alternate: countries with Not Enforced have different turnout commpared to countries without compulsory voting
turnout_notenforced = subset(Turnout, compulsory != "Enforced")
t.test(turnout ~ compulsory, turnout_notenforced)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  turnout by compulsory
## t = 0.55877, df = 7.9204, p-value = 0.5918
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -9.375818 15.358865
## sample estimates:
##           mean in group No mean in group Not Enforced 
##                   67.91867                   64.92714

Pvalue is 0.5918, which is above the 0.05 threshold. Therefore, we cannot reject the null hypothesis and we can conclude that there no difference in voter turnout between countries without compulsory voting and countries that don’t enforce compulsory voting

2.3 Conclusion

Countries should have compulsory voting to increase voter turnout. Also, countries with compulsory voting should enforce it, otherwise there is no point.

Canada does not have compulsory voting. To increase Canadian voter turnout, we should throw scumbags who don’t vote (like Tony) in jail

3 The effect of plurality

Countries using the majoritarian (or plurality) system generally have a lower voter turnout.

Column name is elec.type

This is a boring one - same analysis as previous basically

3.1 Univariate Analysis

ggplot(Turnout, aes(elec.type)) +
  geom_bar()

3.2 Bivariate Anaylsis

ggplot(Turnout, aes(elec.type, turnout)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Doesn’t look like there’s any effect

3.2.1 Statistical test - ANOVA

  • Null: there is no relationship between turnout and elec.type
  • Alternate: there is a relationship between turnout and elec.type
anova(lm(turnout ~ elec.type, Turnout))
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: turnout
##           Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## elec.type  2   667.8  333.91     1.4 0.2531
## Residuals 73 17411.3  238.51

Pvalue is 0.2531, which is greater than the 0.05 cutoff. Therefore, cannot reject the null hypothesis and conclude there is no relationship

3.3 Conclusion

No relationship between elec.type and turnout

4 Effect of electoral competitiveness

Higher electoral competitiveness increases voter turnout

Column name is competitiveness

4.1 Univariate analysis

ggplot(Turnout, aes(competitiveness)) +
  geom_density()
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

Skewed to the right - not normally distributed

4.2 Bivariate analysis

Using scatterplot

ggplot(Turnout, aes(competitiveness, turnout)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=FALSE)
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Observation: looks like a really shitty correlation

4.2.1 Statistical test - R correlation

  • Null hypothesis: true correlation is equal to 0
  • Alternate hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
cor.test(Turnout$competitiveness, Turnout$turnout, use = "complete")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  Turnout$competitiveness and Turnout$turnout
## t = 1.4972, df = 70, p-value = 0.1388
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.05787655  0.39183207
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.1761539

Correlation value is 0.176 which is weak to begin with, and the p-value of this correlation is 0.1388, so cannot reject the null hypothesis that the true correlation is 0

4.3 Conclusion

No relationship bewteen turnout and competitiveness

A country with a population who has higher education will result in a higher voter turnout

Column name is educ

## Warning: Removed 27 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 27 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Observation: seems like there’s a relationship

5.2.1 Statistical test - R correlation

  • Null hypothesis: true correlation is equal to 0
  • Alternate hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
cor.test(Turnout$educ, Turnout$turnout, use = "complete")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  Turnout$educ and Turnout$turnout
## t = 2.6152, df = 47, p-value = 0.01195
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.08359762 0.57953020
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.3564158

Correlation value is 0.3564158 which is a weakly positive relationship, and the p-value of this correlation is 0.01195, so we are at least 95% confident that this correlation value is real

6 Multiple regression

Let’s run a multiple regression using all the columns

turnout_complete = Turnout[complete.cases(Turnout),] #remove rows with missing data

model = lm(turnout ~ elec.year + elec.type + compulsory + competitiveness + democ.type + bicameral + DM + ENPP + years.democ + corrupt + educ + pop, turnout_complete)
